,Recommended,284260,29381210,Posted: 20 January,all,Hattori,"How do you even describe this ""videogame""?In Panoramical, you are given a  template, in which you can move at will the parameters that change that template, creating sounds and objects in the screen  as you do so. Thats pretty much it. Thats the extent of the actual interactivity you have in this game. You procedurally generate sound and visuals.What is really incredible, is how much that small interactivity can create both visually and audibly. Every button in your gamepad adds something to the screen, each with hundreds of possible variations and intensities, and every change creates a new sound that adds up with everything else creating specific and melodic tune.These parameters while very abstract, manage to resemble objects and forms from our own world, and you will soon start to see landscapes and worlds that seem to recall our own planet, but feel completely alien to you at the same time, creating one of the weirdest and coolest experiences I have ever had with procedurally generated games.The tune created alongside the visuals also seems to perfectly match with what you are seeing, creating beautiful tone pieces and abstract moving paintings.You can see how hard it is to describe this game by now.But trust me, its so easy to lose yourself to these worlds you create, and just when you think you have extended fully the limits of a specific canvas, you find something new in a specific parameter that creates a whole new handful of possibilites. you really have to force yourself to stop, just so you can move on to another template, its very easy to lose half an hour in just one place.The experience is just very surreal and immersive, partly due to the constant movements of the figures and shapes on the screen, the camera always seems to move towards the horizon, giving you the feeling of soaring over the mountains and plants you create.It also has 3 specific templates that focus much more on the music side of the experience, and you can actually create some very cool music tracks that seem to have some sort of structure, those are worth checking out as well.Anyways, I tried my best to review this game, but I feel like I did a very bad job at it. I guess you just have to play it to understand what im talking about, but its a very short and sweet ride through the uncanny valley, and if you are the kind of person that takes part in ""special substances"" and zone out for a few hours, then this is for you."
