76561198132098928,Recommended,284260,18129477,"Posted: 21 September, 2015",all,Yasmin,"You find yourself in this ever moving forest of black little hills, shooting purple stars, yellow bubbles and ethereal looking sheets of white. You can manipulate them and change them into something else. The sounds seem to move along with the changes or is it the visuals that move along with the sounds? It doesn't matter. Behind me, my boyfriend tells me later, the cats were breaking down the house, but I was completely oblivious and sucked into my screen. Yes I was on a trip. A journey.allthought I write a lot of reviews for websites and newspapers, this is actually the first time I decided to write something on Steam. I feel like I have to, there are people who don't get this game and I'm not saying that my vision is THE way to interpret it. But it got to me in a way where I just have to share my experience of this game.  Or is it even a game? It acts as a crossover between a game and sound-editing program with trippy visuals. But really I see it as participatory art.It completely rips up the whole concept of 'game' and what we expect of it, and that to me is what makes it even more fascinating. It starts right out with the intro and menu being so incredibly organic, instead of the typical list of buttons you can click, it's a dial that looks almost like a living organism. It's incredibly easy to start 'playing', the controls are very intuitive. I think a game like this encourages natural play a lot more than some other bigger games out there, where you have to follow certain paths in very constrictive ways.The music goes from angelic to stomping to racing and back again, it's mellow and then it's intense. You can adapt it like you are the creator of this little musical universe that keeps on moving and hypnotizing you. It is like you can SEE the music, a concept called synthesia, where the different areas of the brain that control our senses get connected or mixed up. Normally only people with a rare condition, or people on psychedelics get to experience this. And now we can sit behind our screens, completely sober and touch on that magical experience. Allthough I must admit being high makes it even more immersive - if you can handle, try it! Pretty sure that makers had a few trips that inspired them to make this.I must admit thought, if you're sensitive to bright lights and flashy visuals, be careful cause it's VERY intense. I'm glad I'm on preventative medication for migraines, else I would probably, or rather definitely have had an attack from this game. Having said that, I can't really discover anything else that I didn't like about this game.Of course it's a matter of taste if you like it and since it's so different, I'm pretty sure it will be a niche group that will be drawn to this game. But I guess it's the same with art, not everyone likes it in the first place and then there's all the different types of art. If you go to a museum you might pay ten euros for the entrance and look at still lives of similar visuals. Now you get to participate, make music, manipulate visuals and even make sceenshots of your trip. I think it's well worth the money and I would love to see more of the makers.Also I think that it works different than a regular game where you level up and go through the story and then you finish after 50 hours. This is an experience, and I feel I would like to go back to that experience every once in a while, but not hours at a time.After playing this I feel stimulated, refreshed and inspired. Something like a meditation."
