,Recommended,284260,27405171,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,ARAMIS,"PANORAMICAL is less of a game and more of a showcase of what can be done with the symbiosis of audio and visual interaction. Multiple ""stages"" let you adjust and play around with a variety of parameters which will, in turn, change the sound and visuals of whatever landscape you happen to be looking at. One of the more impressive stages takes place in a constantly scrolling brutalist glitch city, which I found could stand on it's own as I played other music over top of the game. Some of the visuals are good for that kind of visualizer stuff.Another thing that has to be mentioned is the soundtrack by David Kanaga (as well as a few other artists in the bonus stages). If you were into the music from Proteus or Dyad you will love this soundtrack. Warped melodies and abstract electronica. Plus the Gershwin cover at the end is amazing. Well worth checking out just to listen.You'll like this if you're looking for more of an experimental tool rather than a conventional capital G game"
76561198040607015,Recommended,284260,31773437,Posted: 15 May,all,M_Triste,"It sounds pretentious, but this game's more of an interactive experience than a typical game. I enjoy going back to it every once in a while to play around with the different ""levels"" - each one is distinct and stimulating in its own way. Sometimes I think it would be nice to be able to control the music separately from the visuals, but it also makes sense thematically to have them integrated.There needs to be more games like this."
